const frontmatter = {
  title: "Autoignition Research (Summer 2025)",
  subtitle: "Reaction mechanisms, surrogate fuels, lab work.",
  reportUrl: "/ColinGraySURF2024FinalReportAll.pdf"
};
---
<ProjectLayout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <div slot="summary">
    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>
    As my first experience with combustion, I learned a lot over this summer. To start, I had to self study a bit of combustion, read through sldies that Professor Shepherd had used for previous classes and search what I didn't understand. After getting a solid foundation, I began to explore my topic of ways to increase the AIT of sustainable fuels to make them safer. 
    To give an overview, I did a few weeks of pure research: finding numbers, adding them to spreadsheets, database searches, and understanding the apparatus I was using. We decided the strongest correlations (that were feasible to test) in pure hydrocarbon components was increased branching and chain length among same size molecules. This was tested just by investigating the performance of relevant surrogate fuels.
    My results matched my hypothesis (as shown in the image below). I successfully presented, pondered, discussed, and justified my results in front of several audiences. I was able to answer all relevant questions regarding my work at conferences and seminars, and I think I still could. This experience <strong>REALLY</strong> put me into the forefront in terms of combustion chemistry knowledge and intuition.
    To read the results and actual research, please skim the report linked above, I spent a LONG time writing it.
     </p>
    
